"Jiang M.Y., Li J.Q., Wu Y.Q., Lin N.T., Wang X.M., Fu F.F.","Chemical characterization of nanometer-sized elemental carbon particles emitted from diesel vehicles",2011,"Journal of Aerosol Science","42","6",,"365","371",,,10.1016/j.jaerosci.2011.03.002,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79953227695&partnerID=40&md5=c2380da18b0eb6f04a86f95b0a4a1c42","Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety of Ministry of Education, Fujian, China; Fujian Provincial Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety, Department of Chemistry, Fuzhou University, Fuzhou, Fujian 350108, China; Department of Chemistry, Fuzhou University, Fuzhou, Fujian 350108, China","Jiang, M.Y., Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety of Ministry of Education, Fujian, China, Fujian Provincial Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety, Department of Chemistry, Fuzhou University, Fuzhou, Fujian 350108, China; Li, J.Q., Department of Chemistry, Fuzhou University, Fuzhou, Fujian 350108, China; Wu, Y.Q., Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety of Ministry of Education, Fujian, China, Fujian Provincial Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety, Department of Chemistry, Fuzhou University, Fuzhou, Fujian 350108, China; Lin, N.T., Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety of Ministry of Education, Fujian, China, Fujian Provincial Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety, Department of Chemistry, Fuzhou University, Fuzhou, Fujian 350108, China; Wang, X.M., Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety of Ministry of Education, Fujian, China, Fujian Provincial Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety, Department of Chemistry, Fuzhou University, Fuzhou, Fujian 350108, China; Fu, F.F., Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety of Ministry of Education, Fujian, China, Fujian Provincial Key Laboratory of Analysis and Detection for Food Safety, Department of Chemistry, Fuzhou University, Fuzhou, Fujian 350108, China","In order to obtain the exact chemical structure and further discuss the global warming effect of elemental carbon (EC) particles, the morphology and the chemical structure of EC particles emitted from diesel vehicles were first investigated in detail using scan electron microscopy equipped with an energy dispersive X-ray spectrometer (SEM-EDX), matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization time-of-flight mass spectrometry (MALDI-TOF-MS), Fourier Transformation Infrared (FT-IR) spectrum and 13C Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) spectrum in this study. The SEM-EDX results showed that EC particles emitted from diesel bus are 50nm spherical particles with smooth surface and an O/C ratio (mass ratio) of 0.07±0.01. The 50nm EC particles were further deduced to be an aggregate of new fullerene C36(OH)2 according to the results of MALDI-TOF-MS, FT-IR and 13C NMR. Fullerenes smaller than 60C were considered to be unstable since they cannot fulfill the so-called isolated pentagon rule. So far, most of our knowledge regarding small fullerenes comes from gas-phase experiments and theoretical investigations, the production and separation of small fullerene solids in the macroscopic quantity has been reported. The present report is the first discovery of C36(OH)2-based solid. © 2011 Elsevier Ltd.","Black carbon particle; Elemental carbon particle; Small fullerene; Soot","Black carbon; Chemical characterization; Chemical structure; Diesel vehicles; Elemental carbon; Elemental carbon particle; Energy dispersive x-ray spectrometers; Fourier transformations; Fullerene C; Gasphase; Isolated-pentagon rules; Macroscopic quantities; MALDI TOF MS; Mass ratio; Matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization-time-of-flight mass spectrometry; Scan electron microscopy; SEM-EDX; Small fullerene; Smooth surface; Spherical particle; Theoretical investigations; Desorption; Diesel locomotives; Fourier analysis; Fourier transforms; F